# Editorial Architecture

## Emergent Series Principle

Articles and Field Notes are standalone by default.

Standalone status refers only to metadata and navigation. It does not imply a different editorial standard, article structure, or content depth.

A standalone article should be treated identically to any article that later becomes part of a series.

## Editorial Standards Remain Identical

Whether or not an article belongs to a series, maintain the existing Tides of Knowing article standards:

- Long-form essay structure.
- Typical target length approximately 2,200-2,500 words, allowing exceptions where warranted.
- Standard headline hierarchy.
- Standard pull quotes and highlighted passages.
- Standard introduction and conclusion structure.
- Standard metadata requirements.
- Standard hero image treatment.
- Standard Further Reading relationships.
- Standard SEO expectations.
- Standard E-E-A-T expectations.
- Standard authority-building posture.

The absence of series metadata does not change the article itself.

## Relationship Hierarchy

Topics answer: "What is this about?"

Further Reading answers: "What should I read next?"

Series answer: "In what order should I read these?"

These are separate concepts and should not be conflated.

## Publishing Rules

When publishing a new article:

- Assume standalone status unless a formal series already exists.
- Do not assign `seriesName`, `seriesOrder`, `seriesTotal`, `previousArticle`, or `nextArticle` merely because future related pieces may be written.
- Continue using the same article architecture, metadata, pull quotes, image treatment, and word-count expectations as any other article.
- Use topics for subject grouping.
- Use Further Reading for conceptual adjacency.

## Retrospective Series Formation

If subsequent articles reveal an ordered conceptual, narrative, or practice arc, series metadata may be added retrospectively.

When this occurs:

- Preserve existing URLs.
- Preserve existing article structure.
- Add series metadata only.
- Create a series landing page.
- Add previous/next navigation.
- Do not imply that the series was planned from the outset.

The article itself should not be rewritten simply because it later becomes part of a series.

## Guiding Principle

Series are discovered, not declared.

Structure follows meaning, not anticipation.

A standalone article today may become part of a series tomorrow, but it should be written and published as a complete article in every sense from the beginning.
